result.execSummary:
The defendant Austin Mitchell Moore was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Operate Firearm While Intoxicated, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 941.20(1)(b).
  • Carry Concealed Weapon, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 941.23(2).

records.addlTxt: REQUEST TO ISSUE CIVIL JUDGMENT FOR COURT OBLIGATION AND/OR RESTITUTION RECEIVED AND FORWARDED TO ALI. OS

Defendant Austin Mitchell Moore in court with attorney Andrew Peter Arena.  Margaret Anne Kunisch appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy court clerk cmt.
Defendant prepared to enter change of plea.  Hearing proceeded.  Negotiations set forth by the state.

As to Counts 1 and 2:  Defendant changes his plea to GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty.   Defendant advised that if not a United States Citizen, deportation is possible.  Court found that defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights.  Guilty Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea.  Court found defendant guilty and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.


Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.    
As to Count 1:  Defendant ordered to serve 4 months in the House of Correction concurrent to Count 2.  Court STAYED the sentence and placed the defendant on probation  for 12 months.

As to Count 2:   Defendant ordered to serve 4 months in the House of Correction concurrent to Count 1.  Court STAYED the sentence and placed the defendant on probation  for 12 months.

Conditions of Probation: 
- Alcohol and drug assessment and comply with any treatment deemed necessary by the department.
- Maintain absolute sobriety.  No illegal drugs.
- Obtain GED/HSED.
- Defendant to pay costs, fees and surcharges during period of probation.  If unpaid a civil judgment will be ordered filed against the defendant.

Court will grant expungement upon successful completion of probation.
